Getting Started

The Apex Trading API provides programmatic access to read Apex Trading data. Retrieve orders, View an order, Retreieve Products, View a products, etc.

This guide will help you get started with the Apex Trading! All the important stuff managing api token's, api authentication, api endpoints, responses, and errors is documented here, but should you have any questions, always feel free to reach out to us at support@apextrading.com or chat with us

To use this API, you need an API token. Please contact us at support@apextrading.com or chat with us to get your own API token.

An API token will have different permissions associated with it that will allow you access to various types of interactions and data within the API.

Definitions
Definition
API Application Programming Interface. The ability to interact with the Apex Trading Application on a programmatic level.
token The secret unique key identifier generated to interact with the Apex Trading API
Permissions The abilities that a token has associated with it that will allow access to specified data and to allow different actions to be performed.
GET Request Retrieve data or an item from the API.
POST Request Create a new item in the API or Perform an Action in the API.
PUT Request Update an existing item in the API.
DELETE Request Delete or disable an existing item in the API.
Authentication

The Apex Trading API endpoints will only establish communication over the HTTPS Secure communication protocol and requires a valid token in order to interact with it using Bearer authentication.

Bearer authentication (also called token authentication) is an HTTP authentication scheme that involves security tokens called bearer tokens. The name "Bearer authentication" can be understood as "give access to the bearer of this token." The bearer token is a cryptic string generated by the server. The client must send this token in the Authorization header when making requests to protected resources.

All API requests are required to have a Authorization header of Bearer YOUR_API_TOKEN_HERE.

All API requests are required to have a Content-Type header of application/json.

All API endpoints make use of the JSON format for sending and receiving data and all POST and PUT requests are expected to contain JSON.

  • Javascript

    Data Nomenclature

    All API requests are required to have a Content-Type header of application/json.

    All API endpoints make use of the JSON format for sending and receiving data and all POST and PUT requests are expected to contain JSON.

    Times and Dates

    All date and date/time fields submited to the server are expected to be in ISO 8601 format. Likewise, all date and date/time fields returned by the server will be in ISO 8601 format.

    The only ISO 8601 date format supported is YYYY-MM-DD, even though the standard defines YYYY-DDD as valid, it is currently not supported.

    Below are some examples of valid ISO 8601 date/time formats:

    Example Description
    2021-04-20 The above date/time format represents April 20th, 2021.
    2021-04-20T22:04:50Z The above date/time format represents April 20th, 2021 10:04:50 PM (UTC) using the Z identifier. The API will assume 000 milliseconds.
    2021-04-20T22:04:50+00:00 The format above represents the same April 20th, 2021 10:04:50 PM (UTC) using a numerical time zone offset of +00:00. The API will assume 000 milliseconds.
    2021-11-02T16:30:40.345+00:00 The format above represents November 2nd, 2021 4:30:40.345 PM (UTC) using a numerical time zone offset of +00:00. Note the addition of the milliseconds portion of the time in this example.
    2021-01-12T22:20:30.456-06:00 The format above represents January 12th, 2021 10:20:30.456 PM (MDT) using a numerical time zone offset of -06:00. Note the addition of the milliseconds portion of the time in this example.
    Currency

    All currency data returned is rounded to the hundredths decimal (1.00) with no symbol($).

    When sending currency query do not include the currency symbol or commas.

    When you send you a currency query you can do so with or without the decimal point ($100 or $100.00).

    Example Server Response of Currency 
    {
    "orders": [
        {
            ...
            "total": "5740.00",
            ...
        }
    ]
}
    Paginations

    The Apex Trading API uses pagination to return its records. The default records per page is 15 records.

    This can be ovridden with the query parameter per_page.

    The maximum records allowed per page is 500 records.

    An example of the paginated return at the bottom of a return request will look similiar to the following:

    Server Responses
    200 OK The request has succeeded.
    201 Created The request has succeeded and a new record has been created as a result.
    401 Unauthorized { "message": "Unauthenticated." }
    403 Forbidden { "message": "This action is unauthorized." }
    404 Not Found { "message": "Resource Not Found" }
    422 Unprocessable Entity { "message": "The given data was invalid." }
    500 Internal Server Error { "message": "Server Error" }

    Quickstart Guide
    1. Obtain a valid token from the api management console
    2. In the header of your request add Content-Type of application/json
    3. In the header of your request add Authorization YOUR_API_TOKEN_HERE
    4. Send a GET Request to https://app.apextrading.com/api/v1
